member.name: T:Woti.WOTI_TradePermActionFlags
member.summary: Defines Trade Permission Flags for actions available to WORMS users. See remarks.
member.remarks:
WORMS uses TradePermBitmasks to communicate about the capabilities of its users. TradePermBitmasks are created by bitwise-ORing elements of this and another enumeration, WOTI_TradePermTypeFlags. WOTI_TradePermActionFlags defines the actions that can be performed within the activity type constaints defined by the active WOTI_TradePermActivityFlags.
The integer values of these flags indicate bit positions in an unsigned TradePermBitmask value. Check if a given flag is set by checking if a bitwise-AND of TradePermBitmask and 1 left-shifted by the desired flag value is not equal to 0. Note that the first bit of the trade perm bitmask is reserved for Invalid.

member.name: T:Woti.WOTI_TradePermTypeFlags
member.summary: Defines Trade Permission Flags that govern the types of activity that WORMS users can undertake. See remarks.
member.remarks:
WORMS uses TradePermBitmasks to communicate about the capabilities of its users. TradePermBitmasks are created by bitwise-ORing elements of this and another enumeration, WOTI_TradePermActionFlags. WOTI_TradePermTypeFlags is significant because it defines the types of activity the Action Flags apply to. The vast majority of users will only be permissioned to work Outright Orders, but if users are also to be allowed access to staged orders, the appropriate staged order bits should also be turned on.
The integer values of these flags indicate bit positions in an unsigned TradePermBitmask value. Check if a given flag is set by checking if a bitwise-AND of TradePermBitmask and 1 left-shifted by the desired flag value is not equal to 0. Note that the first bit of the trade perm bitmask is reserved for Invalid.

member.name: F:Woti.WOTI_EventType.EV_KillPendingReplace
member.summary: Generated when the gateway is halfway through a simulated cancel-replace operation. The original order has been successfully canceled and the replacement order is about to go out to the exchange.
member.remarks: Some exchanges do not natively support ChangeOrder operations. When dealing with these exchanges, a WORMS gateway will cancel the order to be changed and place a new one at the exchange. The WORMS system only shows the existence of one order in this situation, with the ReplacementOrder event serving as the delimeter between the two exchange orders. Note that this procedure (called a "Simulated Cancel-Replace") effects the requested change but has the side effect of causing the order to lose its book position, which may cause it to be filled later than it would have been otherwise.

member.name: T:Woti.UserConfig.CWotiUserConfig
member.summary: Provides access to global WOTI user configuration.
member.remarks: Configuration values are modified via the GlobalConfig application. These case-sensitive values exist to provide users with a way to inform all of their WOTI applications about their personal trading preferences. For instance, a specific route can be associated with a portfolio name. When that portfolio is later specified by the user in WOTI clients, the clients can automatically look up the desired default route setting and populate themselves with that value. It is not required that your application make use of these values. Except for market data settings, no settings configured by the Global Config application are used on any level by the WORMS infrastructure.

member.param: The name of the machine where the WormsSrv is located, with optional colon-separated port number.
The user's firm.

Defines the length of time in seconds that the WORMS Server will expect a heartbeat message from the client. Enter 0 to accept the server default (usually 30 seconds.) Heartbeats are sent automatically by WOTI. If the WORMS Server sees that the client misses 3 heartbeats, the client will be disconnected. WOTI cannot send heartbeats while it is populating the order cache, so this value becomes important if the client must connect to a system that has a large number of orders and needs more time to populate its order cache after LogOn.
Indicates whether the session will automatically log back on if the user is unexpectedly logged off by the server.
The name of the application logging on to the WORMS system.

member.name: E:Woti.Orders.CWormsOrderCache.OrderUpdated
member.summary: This fires when a viewable order is updated. It provides references to the specific event which triggered the update as well as the affected CWormsOrder. It also indicates whether or not this update is a part of a batch. See Remarks for more details.
member.remarks:
Order updates for certain advanced operations (such as allocations or a move-to-portfolio) can arrive in batches. When an update batch has been received, bLastUpdateInBatch will become false for every update except the last one in the batch. For the more common operations where there is only one associated update, bLastUpdateInBatch will be true.
Best practice is to refrain from taking action based on an update with bLastUpdateInBatch=false. A false bLastUpdateInBatch value indicates that your application has not yet received all WORMS updates and is therefore not fully aware of the actual system status. You should record the information contained in each update and withhold any reaction until the entire batch has arrived.
It is worth noting that once the first element of a batch update is transmitted to your application, all subsequent elements of the batch will be transmitted in sequence. No updates from outside the batch will be transmitted until after you receive the final batch update.
